<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-635-996  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 635 996.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Canadian Datasystems  June 1990 v22 n6 p52(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mainframe punch from micro purse. (Using parallel processing tomeet computer needs, not exceed them) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>White, Ted.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer systems in the 1990s will use microcomputers asmultiprocessing workstations, operating individually for usualapplications and combining resources for peak processing needs.andO;Most computer users need only limited computer resources, while afew power users lack the speed and memory required for complexapplications.andP;  New computer systems pool workstation resources toprovide power users with the resources of a mainframe computer,while avoiding the expense of large central computer systems.andO;These microcomputer systems also avoid the upgrade expense ofindividual microcomputers, because less powerful machines arestill useful for most applications.andP;  For guidelines for selectingparallel microprocessing systems are given.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MultiprocessingMicrocomputersWorkstationsModularityIntegrated SystemsOutlook.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>